As we all know, a large part of success in college depends on the accessability of college services and information.
Westchester Community College is home to a highly diverse group of traditional and non-traditional students, coming from many backgrounds and many levels of computer or technical aptitude.
There is a larger trend going on today, where mobile phones are increasingly becoming an individual's main (or only!) tie to the internet as a whole.

Last Friday, I had the opportunity to speak to Professor Christine Thomas at the Center for Student Success, about our development of WCC's mobile app. The following represents my personal understanding and outlines of the situation, based on that initial conference.
Other colleges and universities have apps too. Let's see what they look like.
The following represents a brief survey of existing, comparable software.

-Stores user-defined preferences and properties (Display Sub-Apps as grid, as list, include search bar, etc)

-Presents searchable, interactable database of WCC faculty contacts, with detail pages

Professor Thomas had indicated a desire for a parent-app/sub-app format. As it turns out, this is exactly the layout used by the vast majority of other colleges.
She came up with a rough list of the following sub-apps:
